\pard\plain \tx562\tx1123\tx1685\tx2246\tx2808\tx3370\tx3931\tx4493\tx5054\tx5616\tx6178\tx6739\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 If a scene is too extensive to fit into a single message and needs to be broken into parts, you can follow a similar approach to maintain continuity and ensure that I understand these parts make up a single scene:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 Divide the Scene into Logical Parts: Break the scene into logical segments that can be sent in separate messages. These could be based on shifts in action, dialogue, or focus within the scene.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 Label Each Part Clearly: When you send each part, label it clearly to indicate its place in the sequence. This will help me understand that each message is a continuation of the same scene.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 Provide Context or Transition if Needed: If necessary, include a brief recap or transition to link the parts together. This might be useful if there's a gap in time between sending the different parts.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 Explicitly State Your Intent: Make it clear from the beginning that the messages are parts of a single scene and that they should be treated as one continuous narrative.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 For example, your messages could be structured like:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs26\b0\i0 "Scene 0200, Part 1: Evan waits for Sarah at the parking lot..."}
